lfish, egoistical and probably with a minor personality disorder. Part of school is learning the ability to deal with different types of people and develop as a person, not just about the knowledge taken in by the child. Taking that interaction away from children is cruel. Replacing it with Scouts or visits with other home schooled children is not the same. &#10;To use bullying \ poor standards \ any other excuse to dismiss a whole system of education is mypoic. I believe some children probably do benefit from home schooling, in the same way a select few benefit from tuition, that doesn't make it right IMO. Sorry. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="917" language="en" documentId="1107" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="calminthestorm" date="28 July 2010 11:57pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6871246" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="1" thumbsDown="0" origId="1107" notes="" title="Home education: precious, not dangerous"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="56"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="57" end="140"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="141" end="659"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="660" end="917"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>